description:
I have added extra photos of this hornbeam because someone on here suggested this was an elm, but it is definitely a hornbeam. Note: it has smooth grey bark (elms have rough bark); you can see the remains of the male inflorescence with its short bracts (whereas in elms the flowers are purplish and globular).  The leaves display the double-toothed margins and pleating. 
Also I have walked past this particular tree many times when it has been bearing its distinctive hornbeam ribbed nuts within their trident-shaped leafy bracts (whereas elm fruits are nuts encased in a thin papery, oval-round wing.
This is Lesser. Known because this one is all over the park and I've checked the inflorescence arrangement before to see which burdock it is.

Goat willow or a hybrid of S. capraea x Salix sp 
I've added a couple more pix today, as someone was asking about it being a hybrid.
